{"title_page": "Summer Nights (Grease song)", "text_new": "{{redirect|Summer Loving}}\n{{short description|1978 single by John Travolta and Olivia Newton-John}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Summer Nights (''Grease'' song)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Summer Nights\n| image      = Summer Nights by John Travolta, Olivia Newton-John, and cast Australian vinyl Side-A.png\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Side-A label of 1978 Australian vinyl single\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[John Travolta]] and [[Olivia Newton-John]]\n| album      = [[Grease: The Original Soundtrack from the Motion Picture]]\n| B-side     = \"Rock and Roll Party Queen\" (performed by [[Louis St. Louis]])\n| released   = August 25, 1978\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[musical theatre]]\n| length     = 3:35\n| label      = [[RSO Records|RSO]]\n| writer     = [[Jim Jacobs]], [[Warren Casey]]\n| producer   =\n| chronology = [[Olivia Newton-John]] single\n| prev_title = [[You're the One That I Want]]\n| prev_year  = 1978\n| next_title = [[Hopelessly Devoted to You]]\n| next_year  = 1978\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[John Travolta]]\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[You're the One That I Want]]\n | prev_year  = 1978\n | title      = Summer Nights\n | year       = 1978\n | next_title = Sandy\n | next_year  = 1978\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Summer Nights'''\" is a [[popular song]] from the musical ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]''. Written by [[Jim Jacobs]] and [[Warren Casey]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0077631/soundtrack |title=Grease (1978) - Soundtracks|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2014-03-28}}</ref> its best-known version was recorded by [[John Travolta]] and [[Olivia Newton-John]] for the [[Grease (film)|big-screen adaptation]] of the musical, and released as a single that same year.\n\n\"Summer Nights\" became a massive hit in both the United States and United Kingdom during the summer of 1978. Included on the movie's [[Grease: The Original Soundtrack from the Motion Picture|soundtrack album]], the song was one of several hit singles from the movie. Parts of the song were introduced to a new audience when it was re-released in the 1990s as part of a [[megamix]] of several songs from the movie version.\n\n==Background==\nIn the movie version of ''Grease'', Travolta and Newton-John played the lead roles of Danny Zuko and Sandy Olsson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0077631|title= Grease (1978)|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2014-03-28}}</ref>\n\nThe song's genesis stems from a summertime love affair between Danny and Sandy, which had ended upon Sandy's revelation that she was moving back to Australia with her family. However, Sandy soon learns that her family is staying in the United States and subsequently enrolls at Rydell High School, where Danny is also a student. (In the original stage version, Sandy Dumbrowski, who like many other characters in the play is a Catholic of Polish descent, originally attends parochial school. On the other hand, Danny lied to her and claimed to attend [[Lake Forest Academy]], a prestigious real-life private school in Chicago. Sandy's parents' decision to pull her out of Catholic school and put her in public Rydell High exposes Danny's ruse.) However, it quickly becomes clear that there are unresolved feelings of love between Danny and Sandy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0077631/plotsummary|title= Grease (1978) - Plot Summary|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2014-03-28}}</ref>\n\nSeparately and unknown to each other, both Danny and Sandy meet with their respective group of friends and share their perspectives of their summertime fling. Danny, the leader of a greaser gang known as \"The T-Birds\" (the \"Burger Palace Boys\" in the stage show), brags about the physical aspects of the relationship; Sandy remarks to the schoolgirl clique \"The Pink Ladies\" about her emotional attachment to Danny. The resulting conversations are played out through the song.\n\nOf the cast members, only Travolta and Newton-John provided vocals for the previous single from the soundtrack, \"[[You're The One That I Want]]\", but other members of the cast contributed backing and cameo lead vocals to \"Summer Nights\". The only vocal contributions on the soundtrack from [[Kelly Ward]] (Putzie) and [[Michael Tucci]] (Sonny) are their single questions in this song (Sonny also had no solo lines in the musical; the two songs from the musical by Putzie's stage counterpart were cut from the film). [[Stockard Channing]] (Rizzo)'s solo line \"'Cause he sounds like a drag\" was spoken rather than sung. The background lyrics quote two songs, \"[[Da Doo Ron Ron]]\" by [[The Crystals]] and \"[[Papa-Oom-Mow-Mow]]\" by [[The Rivingtons]] (later made famous as Part 2 of \"[[Surfin' Bird]]\" by [[The Trashmen]]), that were released in 1963; this is an anachronism, as the song is set in fall 1958.\n\n\"Summer Nights\" was originally written for the stage show's transition to Broadway. The original Chicago version of the musical (staged only once since the 1970s) had a different song, \"Foster Beach,\" at that point.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bring back our own, original R-rated 'Grease'|url=http://leisureblogs.chicagotribune.com/the_theater_loop/2009/01/bring-back-our.html|accessdate=28 June 2015|date=8 January 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131117163229/http://leisureblogs.chicagotribune.com/the_theater_loop/2009/01/bring-back-our.html|archivedate=17 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Chart success==\n\"Summer Nights\" reached No. 5 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cylist.com/List/400300168 |title=Billboard Top 40 Hits (1978) at cyList |publisher=Cylist.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-12}}</ref> and spent two weeks at No. 3 on ''[[Cash Box (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19781007.html |title=Cash Box Top 100 10/07/78 |publisher=50.6.195.142 |date=1978-10-07 |access-date=2014-05-01 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140423020434/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19781007.html |archive-date=2014-04-23 |df= }}]</ref> The song was an even bigger hit in the UK, spending seven weeks at No. 1.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| pages= 357\u20139}}</ref> Combined with an earlier nine-week run with \"You're the One That I Want,\" the Travolta-Newton-John duet team spent 16 weeks at No. 1 during 1978 in the UK.\n\nIn 2004, the song finished at #70 in [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]] survey of top tunes in American cinema.\n\nIn 2010, ''Billboard'' ranked it No. 9 on their \"Best Summer Songs of All Time\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/list/513566/top-30-summer-songs |title=Top 30 Summer Songs |publisher=Billboard.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-12}}</ref>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly singles charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1978)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Kent Music Report|Australia]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Canadian Singles Chart|Canada]] Top Singles (''RPM'')\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Canadian Singles Chart|Canada]] Adult Contemporary (''RPM'')\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[German Singles Chart|Germany]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|1|song=Summer Nights|accessdate=September 10, 2018}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|New Zealand]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio]])<ref>{{cite web|title=SA Charts 1965\u2013March 1989|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(T).html|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]] <ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]])<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' \u2013 {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. (''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19780617.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-06-25 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626131347/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19780617.html |archive-date=2015-06-26 |df= }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. [[Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks|Adult Contemporary]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|21\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1978)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Australia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austchartbook.com.au/ |title=Australian Chart Book |website=Austchartbook.com.au |date= |access-date=2016-10-13 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305064644/http://www.austchartbook.com.au/ |archive-date=2016-03-05 |df= }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|62\n|-\n|Canada<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.0070a&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.0070a.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.0070a |title=Image : RPM Weekly \u2013 Library and Archives Canada |website=Bac-lac.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|42\n|-\n|New Zealand<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/?chart=3867 |title=Top Selling Singles of 1978 &#124; The Official New Zealand Music Chart |website=Nztop40.co.nz |date=1978-12-31 |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref> \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|47\n|-\n|UK<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everyhit.com/chart3.html |title=1970s Singles Chart Archive |website=everyHit.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1978.htm |title=Top 100 Hits of 1978/Top 100 Songs of 1978 |website=Musicoutfitters.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|69\n|-\n|U.S. ''Cash Box''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1978YESP.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-11-03 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304022545/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1978YESP.html |archive-date=2016-03-04 |df= }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|41\n|}\n\n===Decade-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1970\u201379)\n!Rank\n|-\n|UK Singles ([[UK Singles Chart|Official Charts Company]])<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Top 100 Singles of the Decade |url=http://scans.chartarchive.org/UK/1979/TOP%20100%20Singles%20and%20Albums%201970-1979.pdf |magazine=[[Record Mirror]] |location=London |publisher=Spotlight Publications |page=2 |date=January 5, 1980 |access-date=June 19, 2016 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Sales and certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Canada|title=Summer Nights|artist=Olivia Newton-John|award=Gold|certyear=1978|accessdate=15 April 2012|salesamount=75,000}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=France|title=Summer Nights|artist=John Travolta & Olivia Newton-John|award=Gold|certyear=1978|certref=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/S_Certif_Or.php?debut=468|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130213103954/http://www.infodisc.fr/S_Certif_Or.php?debut=468|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 February 2013|title=Les Singles en Or :|publisher=Infodisc.fr|language=French|access-date=29 March 2012}}</ref>|salesref=<ref name=\"Best-selling singles in France\">{{cite web |url=http://www.infodisc.fr/S_ToutTemps.php |title=InfoDisc : Les 45 T. / Singles les plus vendus en France |publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]] |date= |access-date=2012-03-29 |language=French |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/66RlpkRVx?url=http://www.infodisc.fr/S_ToutTemps.php |archive-date=2012-03-26 |df= }}</ref>|accessdate=15 April 2012|salesamount=539,000}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|title=Summer Nights|artist=Olivia Newton-John & John Travolta|award=Platinum|certyear=1978|salesamount=1,640,000|salesref=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/huge-selling-summer-songs-including-grease-calvin-harris-and-bryan-adams__19476/|title=Huge selling 'summer' songs on the Official Chart|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=21 June 2017|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=22 June 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|title=Summer Nights|artist=Newton-John, Olivia and John Travolta|accessdate=15 April 2012|award=Gold|relyear=1978|salesamount=1,000,000}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| '''Total sales:'''\n| \n| '''3,214,000'''\n|-\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==\"The Grease Megamix\"==\nIn 1991, \"Summer Nights\" and two other songs from the ''Grease'' soundtrack \u2014 \"You're The One That I Want\" and \"[[Those Magic Changes|Greased Lightnin']]\" \u2014 were remixed into a new song called \"[[The Grease Megamix]]\". This song was created to observe the movie's release on home video.\n\nJoe Masciantonio, from Outstanding Bass Productions, created the song for Philadelphia radio station [[WIOQ|WIOQ-FM]]. The song subsequently became a big hit worldwide.\n\n==Cover versions==\n* [[Ang\u00e9lica Mar\u00eda]] and Ra\u00fal Vale recorded a [[Spanish language|Spanish-language]] cover titled \"Noches de verano\", which [[List of number-one hits of 1979 (Mexico)|reached #1 in Mexico in 1979.]]\n* Brighton indie band [[14 Iced Bears]] covered the song in 1990, for \"Alvin Lives (In Leeds)\", a compilation of covers of '70s hits released to raise funds for the Anti Poll Tax Campaign.\n* Ska-punk band [[Less Than Jake]] covered the song on their 1996 EP \"[[Greased]]\".\n* In 2012, the cast of the musical TV series ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'', with [[Chord Overstreet]] and [[Amber Riley]] (portraying [[Sam Evans]] and [[Mercedes Jones]] respectively) on lead, performed the song in the tenth episode of [[Glee (season 3)|season three]], \"[[Yes/No (Glee)|Yes/No]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://video.vulture.com/video/Glee-Summer-Nights'''Music'''#c=SQMXY91BXLSZRQTD&t=Glee |title=Glee: 'Summer Nights' |publisher=Video.vulture.com |accessdate=2014-03-28}}</ref>\n* TV Series Korea Dream High 2 \"Jr & Ailee \u2013 Summer Nights\"\n* In May 2004, on Jimmy Fallon's last regular cast appearance on Saturday Night Live, Jimmy and Tina Fey covered \"Summer Nights\" with the rest of the SNL cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0694859/|title=Saturday Night Live (1975\u2013 ) : Mary-Kate & Ashley Olsen/J-Kwon|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n* The 2004 video game [[Leisure Suit Larry: Magna Cum Laude]] includes a minigame set in a gay bar that parodies the song called \"Lesbian Nights\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gvFMlhoxRCU |title=Leisure Suit Larry Gay Song |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2006-09-27 |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n* The song was rewritten for a 2012 [[Nissan]] [[television commercial]] campaign for the \"Summer 'Savin Days\" sales event. The ads feature the [[Nissan Altima]], [[Nissan Frontier]] and [[Nissan Rogue]] among other [[Nissan]] models.\n* In 2011, the guitar riff in the song \"[[What Makes You Beautiful]]\" by boy band [[One Direction]] has been criticized being similar to the original classic song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/review/a338401/one-direction-what-makes-you-beautiful-single-review.html |title=One Direction: 'What Makes You Beautiful' \u2013 Single review |publisher=Digital Spy |date= |accessdate=2014-03-28}}</ref>\n* [[Eden Sher]] sang the song as her character, [[List of The Middle characters#Sue Heck|Sue Heck]], on the [[List of The Middle episodes|100th episode]] of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] comedy series, ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]''. The episode premiered on October 23, 2013.\n* In 2013, a cover version by [[Karmin]] was featured in a [[Twizzlers]] commercial.\n*In the episode \"[[Parks and Recreation (season 6)|The Cones of Dunshire]]\" of the NBC series \"[[Parks and Recreation]]\", a karaoke version was performed by Leslie Knope ([[Amy Poehler]]) and Jeremy Jamm ([[Jon Glaser]]).\n* In the episode \"Crazy for You\" of [[The CW]] series \"[[The Flash (2014 TV series)|The Flash]]\", a karaoke version was performed by Caitlin ([[Danielle Panabaker]]) and Barry Allen ([[Grant Gustin]]).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Grease}}\n{{Olivia Newton-John singles}}\n\n[[Category:1978 singles]]\n[[Category:European Hot 100 Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:John Travolta songs]]\n[[Category:Olivia Newton-John songs]]\n[[Category:Songs from Grease (film)]]\n[[Category:Songs from Grease (musical)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jim Jacobs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Warren Casey]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Male\u2013female vocal duets]]\n[[Category:1972 songs]]\n[[Category:RSO Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1978 single by John Travolta and Olivia Newton-John}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Summer Nights (''Grease'' song)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Summer Nights\n| image      = Summer Nights by John Travolta, Olivia Newton-John, and cast Australian vinyl Side-A.png\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Side-A label of 1978 Australian vinyl single\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[John Travolta]] and [[Olivia Newton-John]]\n| album      = [[Grease: The Original Soundtrack from the Motion Picture]]\n| B-side     = \"Rock and Roll Party Queen\" (performed by [[Louis St. Louis]])\n| released   = August 25, 1978\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[musical theatre]]\n| length     = 3:35\n| label      = [[RSO Records|RSO]]\n| writer     = [[Jim Jacobs]], [[Warren Casey]]\n| producer   =\n| chronology = [[Olivia Newton-John]] single\n| prev_title = [[You're the One That I Want]]\n| prev_year  = 1978\n| next_title = [[Hopelessly Devoted to You]]\n| next_year  = 1978\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[John Travolta]]\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[You're the One That I Want]]\n | prev_year  = 1978\n | title      = Summer Nights\n | year       = 1978\n | next_title = Sandy\n | next_year  = 1978\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Summer Nights'''\" is a [[popular song]] from the musical ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]''. Written by [[Jim Jacobs]] and [[Warren Casey]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0077631/soundtrack |title=Grease (1978) - Soundtracks|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2014-03-28}}</ref> its best-known version was recorded by [[John Travolta]] and [[Olivia Newton-John]] for the [[Grease (film)|big-screen adaptation]] of the musical, and released as a single that same year.\n\n\"Summer Nights\" became a massive hit in both the United States and United Kingdom during the summer of 1978. Included on the movie's [[Grease: The Original Soundtrack from the Motion Picture|soundtrack album]], the song was one of several hit singles from the movie. Parts of the song were introduced to a new audience when it was re-released in the 1990s as part of a [[megamix]] of several songs from the movie version.\n\n==Background==\nIn the movie version of ''Grease'', Travolta and Newton-John played the lead roles of Danny Zuko and Sandy Olsson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0077631|title= Grease (1978)|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2014-03-28}}</ref>\n\nThe song's genesis stems from a summertime love affair between Danny and Sandy, which had ended upon Sandy's revelation that she was moving back to Australia with her family. However, Sandy soon learns that her family is staying in the United States and subsequently enrolls at Rydell High School, where Danny is also a student. (In the original stage version, Sandy Dumbrowski, who like many other characters in the play is a Catholic of Polish descent, originally attends parochial school. On the other hand, Danny lied to her and claimed to attend [[Lake Forest Academy]], a prestigious real-life private school in Chicago. Sandy's parents' decision to pull her out of Catholic school and put her in public Rydell High exposes Danny's ruse.) However, it quickly becomes clear that there are unresolved feelings of love between Danny and Sandy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0077631/plotsummary|title= Grease (1978) - Plot Summary|publisher=IMDb.com|accessdate=2014-03-28}}</ref>\n\nSeparately and unknown to each other, both Danny and Sandy meet with their respective group of friends and share their perspectives of their summertime fling. Danny, the leader of a greaser gang known as \"The T-Birds\" (the \"Burger Palace Boys\" in the stage show), brags about the physical aspects of the relationship; Sandy remarks to the schoolgirl clique \"The Pink Ladies\" about her emotional attachment to Danny. The resulting conversations are played out through the song.\n\nOf the cast members, only Travolta and Newton-John provided vocals for the previous single from the soundtrack, \"[[You're The One That I Want]]\", but other members of the cast contributed backing and cameo lead vocals to \"Summer Nights\". The only vocal contributions on the soundtrack from [[Kelly Ward]] (Putzie) and [[Michael Tucci]] (Sonny) are their single questions in this song (Sonny also had no solo lines in the musical; the two songs from the musical by Putzie's stage counterpart were cut from the film). [[Stockard Channing]] (Rizzo)'s solo line \"'Cause he sounds like a drag\" was spoken rather than sung. The background lyrics quote two songs, \"[[Da Doo Ron Ron]]\" by [[The Crystals]] and \"[[Papa-Oom-Mow-Mow]]\" by [[The Rivingtons]] (later made famous as Part 2 of \"[[Surfin' Bird]]\" by [[The Trashmen]]), that were released in 1963; this is an anachronism, as the song is set in fall 1958.\n\n\"Summer Nights\" was originally written for the stage show's transition to Broadway. The original Chicago version of the musical (staged only once since the 1970s) had a different song, \"Foster Beach,\" at that point.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bring back our own, original R-rated 'Grease'|url=http://leisureblogs.chicagotribune.com/the_theater_loop/2009/01/bring-back-our.html|accessdate=28 June 2015|date=8 January 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131117163229/http://leisureblogs.chicagotribune.com/the_theater_loop/2009/01/bring-back-our.html|archivedate=17 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Chart success==\n\"Summer Nights\" reached No. 5 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cylist.com/List/400300168 |title=Billboard Top 40 Hits (1978) at cyList |publisher=Cylist.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-12}}</ref> and spent two weeks at No. 3 on ''[[Cash Box (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19781007.html |title=Cash Box Top 100 10/07/78 |publisher=50.6.195.142 |date=1978-10-07 |access-date=2014-05-01 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140423020434/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19781007.html |archive-date=2014-04-23 |df= }}]</ref> The song was an even bigger hit in the UK, spending seven weeks at No. 1.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| pages= 357\u20139}}</ref> Combined with an earlier nine-week run with \"You're the One That I Want,\" the Travolta-Newton-John duet team spent 16 weeks at No. 1 during 1978 in the UK.\n\nIn 2004, the song finished at #70 in [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]] survey of top tunes in American cinema.\n\nIn 2010, ''Billboard'' ranked it No. 9 on their \"Best Summer Songs of All Time\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/list/513566/top-30-summer-songs |title=Top 30 Summer Songs |publisher=Billboard.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-12}}</ref>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly singles charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1978)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Kent Music Report|Australia]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Canadian Singles Chart|Canada]] Top Singles (''RPM'')\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Canadian Singles Chart|Canada]] Adult Contemporary (''RPM'')\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[German Singles Chart|Germany]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|1|song=Summer Nights|accessdate=September 10, 2018}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|New Zealand]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio]])<ref>{{cite web|title=SA Charts 1965\u2013March 1989|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(T).html|accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|9\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]] <ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]])<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' \u2013 {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. (''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19780617.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-06-25 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626131347/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19780617.html |archive-date=2015-06-26 |df= }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. [[Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks|Adult Contemporary]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|21\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1978)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Australia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austchartbook.com.au/ |title=Australian Chart Book |website=Austchartbook.com.au |date= |access-date=2016-10-13 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305064644/http://www.austchartbook.com.au/ |archive-date=2016-03-05 |df= }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|62\n|-\n|Canada<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.0070a&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.0070a.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.0070a |title=Image : RPM Weekly \u2013 Library and Archives Canada |website=Bac-lac.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|42\n|-\n|New Zealand<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/?chart=3867 |title=Top Selling Singles of 1978 &#124; The Official New Zealand Music Chart |website=Nztop40.co.nz |date=1978-12-31 |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref> \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|47\n|-\n|UK<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everyhit.com/chart3.html |title=1970s Singles Chart Archive |website=everyHit.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1978.htm |title=Top 100 Hits of 1978/Top 100 Songs of 1978 |website=Musicoutfitters.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|69\n|-\n|U.S. ''Cash Box''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1978YESP.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-11-03 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304022545/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1978YESP.html |archive-date=2016-03-04 |df= }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|41\n|}\n\n===Decade-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1970\u201379)\n!Rank\n|-\n|UK Singles ([[UK Singles Chart|Official Charts Company]])<ref>{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Top 100 Singles of the Decade |url=http://scans.chartarchive.org/UK/1979/TOP%20100%20Singles%20and%20Albums%201970-1979.pdf |magazine=[[Record Mirror]] |location=London |publisher=Spotlight Publications |page=2 |date=January 5, 1980 |access-date=June 19, 2016 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Sales and certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Canada|title=Summer Nights|artist=Olivia Newton-John|award=Gold|certyear=1978|accessdate=15 April 2012|salesamount=75,000}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=France|title=Summer Nights|artist=John Travolta & Olivia Newton-John|award=Gold|certyear=1978|certref=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/S_Certif_Or.php?debut=468|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130213103954/http://www.infodisc.fr/S_Certif_Or.php?debut=468|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 February 2013|title=Les Singles en Or :|publisher=Infodisc.fr|language=French|access-date=29 March 2012}}</ref>|salesref=<ref name=\"Best-selling singles in France\">{{cite web |url=http://www.infodisc.fr/S_ToutTemps.php |title=InfoDisc : Les 45 T. / Singles les plus vendus en France |publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]] |date= |access-date=2012-03-29 |language=French |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/66RlpkRVx?url=http://www.infodisc.fr/S_ToutTemps.php |archive-date=2012-03-26 |df= }}</ref>|accessdate=15 April 2012|salesamount=539,000}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|title=Summer Nights|artist=Olivia Newton-John & John Travolta|award=Platinum|certyear=1978|salesamount=1,640,000|salesref=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/huge-selling-summer-songs-including-grease-calvin-harris-and-bryan-adams__19476/|title=Huge selling 'summer' songs on the Official Chart|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=21 June 2017|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=22 June 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|title=Summer Nights|artist=Newton-John, Olivia and John Travolta|accessdate=15 April 2012|award=Gold|relyear=1978|salesamount=1,000,000}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| '''Total sales:'''\n| \n| '''3,214,000'''\n|-\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==\"The Grease Megamix\"==\nIn 1991, \"Summer Nights\" and two other songs from the ''Grease'' soundtrack \u2014 \"You're The One That I Want\" and \"[[Those Magic Changes|Greased Lightnin']]\" \u2014 were remixed into a new song called \"[[The Grease Megamix]]\". This song was created to observe the movie's release on home video.\n\nJoe Masciantonio, from Outstanding Bass Productions, created the song for Philadelphia radio station [[WIOQ|WIOQ-FM]]. The song subsequently became a big hit worldwide.\n\n==Cover versions==\n* [[Ang\u00e9lica Mar\u00eda]] and Ra\u00fal Vale recorded a [[Spanish language|Spanish-language]] cover titled \"Noches de verano\", which [[List of number-one hits of 1979 (Mexico)|reached #1 in Mexico in 1979.]]\n* Brighton indie band [[14 Iced Bears]] covered the song in 1990, for \"Alvin Lives (In Leeds)\", a compilation of covers of '70s hits released to raise funds for the Anti Poll Tax Campaign.\n* Ska-punk band [[Less Than Jake]] covered the song on their 1996 EP \"[[Greased]]\".\n* In 2012, the cast of the musical TV series ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'', with [[Chord Overstreet]] and [[Amber Riley]] (portraying [[Sam Evans]] and [[Mercedes Jones]] respectively) on lead, performed the song in the tenth episode of [[Glee (season 3)|season three]], \"[[Yes/No (Glee)|Yes/No]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://video.vulture.com/video/Glee-Summer-Nights'''Music'''#c=SQMXY91BXLSZRQTD&t=Glee |title=Glee: 'Summer Nights' |publisher=Video.vulture.com |accessdate=2014-03-28}}</ref>\n* TV Series Korea Dream High 2 \"Jr & Ailee \u2013 Summer Nights\"\n* In May 2004, on Jimmy Fallon's last regular cast appearance on Saturday Night Live, Jimmy and Tina Fey covered \"Summer Nights\" with the rest of the SNL cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0694859/|title=Saturday Night Live (1975\u2013 ) : Mary-Kate & Ashley Olsen/J-Kwon|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n* The 2004 video game [[Leisure Suit Larry: Magna Cum Laude]] includes a minigame set in a gay bar that parodies the song called \"Lesbian Nights\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gvFMlhoxRCU |title=Leisure Suit Larry Gay Song |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2006-09-27 |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n* The song was rewritten for a 2012 [[Nissan]] [[television commercial]] campaign for the \"Summer 'Savin Days\" sales event. The ads feature the [[Nissan Altima]], [[Nissan Frontier]] and [[Nissan Rogue]] among other [[Nissan]] models.\n* In 2011, the guitar riff in the song \"[[What Makes You Beautiful]]\" by boy band [[One Direction]] has been criticized being similar to the original classic song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/review/a338401/one-direction-what-makes-you-beautiful-single-review.html |title=One Direction: 'What Makes You Beautiful' \u2013 Single review |publisher=Digital Spy |date= |accessdate=2014-03-28}}</ref>\n* [[Eden Sher]] sang the song as her character, [[List of The Middle characters#Sue Heck|Sue Heck]], on the [[List of The Middle episodes|100th episode]] of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] comedy series, ''[[The Middle (TV series)|The Middle]]''. The episode premiered on October 23, 2013.\n* In 2013, a cover version by [[Karmin]] was featured in a [[Twizzlers]] commercial.\n*In the episode \"[[Parks and Recreation (season 6)|The Cones of Dunshire]]\" of the NBC series \"[[Parks and Recreation]]\", a karaoke version was performed by Leslie Knope ([[Amy Poehler]]) and Jeremy Jamm ([[Jon Glaser]]).\n* In the episode \"Crazy for You\" of [[The CW]] series \"[[The Flash (2014 TV series)|The Flash]]\", a karaoke version was performed by Caitlin ([[Danielle Panabaker]]) and Barry Allen ([[Grant Gustin]]).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Grease}}\n{{Olivia Newton-John singles}}\n\n[[Category:1978 singles]]\n[[Category:European Hot 100 Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:John Travolta songs]]\n[[Category:Olivia Newton-John songs]]\n[[Category:Songs from Grease (film)]]\n[[Category:Songs from Grease (musical)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Jim Jacobs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Warren Casey]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Male\u2013female vocal duets]]\n[[Category:1972 songs]]\n[[Category:RSO Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "Thryduulf", "label": "safe", "comment": "add hatnote", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Summer_Nights_(Grease_song)"}
